TEXT 1032 616 Left 2 ;This amp reproduces the Jfet amplifier with the same fidelity : \nClipping is very similar (FFTs are almost matching for high gain) and overall\nAC performances are the same over the whole frequency range.\n \nHowever for mid gain (50%), FFT shows that the opAmp produces much more high frequencies harmonics\nthan the JFet one. Harmonic content is around the same up until 20kHz.\nHigher harmonics are heavily suppressed on both implementations (-20dB starting from 10kHz)\n \nAnother side note : for the opAmp to compete with the JFet amp regarding the final waveform amplitude, we need\nit to be a "Rail to Rail" opamp.\nWith a 9V power supply that's really 9V peak to peak that we are observing on the 2 amps, with an input signal of 400mVPeaktoPeak.
TEXT 1032 992 Left 4 ;=> Conclusion : There is no particular advantage whatsoever to use a discrete \nJFet based differential amplifier + PNP transistor to beef up the signal where a \nsingle Rail to Rail OpAmp will do the job just fine with the same gain parameters.
